statement:
\textbf{Full-Solution Problem.} Justify your answer and \textbf{show all
your work.} Simplification of the answer is not required.

Evaluate the following integral\begin{align*}\int \frac{x^2-9}{x(x^2+9)}dx.\end{align*}

sols:
We want to evaluate the integral

\begin{align*}\int \frac{x^2-9}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx.\end{align*}

As a first step, we split up the integral:

\begin{align*}\int \frac{x^2-9}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx = \intÂ \frac{x^2}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx - \int \frac{9}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx\end{align*}

We can evaluate the first integral by canceling a factor of \emph{x},
and then substitute \emph{u= x\^{}2+9}, \emph{du = 2dx}:

\begin{align*} \int \frac{x^2}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx &= \int \frac{x}{x^2+9}\,dx = \int \frac1{2u}\,du \\
&= \frac12\ln|u| + C = \frac12\ln(x^2+9) + C\end{align*}

The second integral can be evaluated using a partial fraction
decomposition

\begin{align*}\frac{-9}{x(x^2+9)} = \frac{A}{x} + \frac{Bx}{x^2+9} + \frac{C}{x^2+9},\end{align*}

which we can solve for $-9 = A(x^2+9) + Bx^2 + Cx.$ When \emph{x = -1},
we get \emph{-9 = 10A+B-C}, when \emph{x=1}, we get \emph{-9 = 10A+B+C}.
Subtracting the two equations gives \emph{C = 0}. Finally, when \emph{x
= 2}, we get \emph{-9 = 13A + 4B}. So \emph{10A + B = 13 A+ 4B}, which
yields \emph{A = -B}. Thus \emph{-9 = 10A-A = 9A}, so that \emph{A = -1}
and \emph{B = 1}. Therefore

\begin{align*}\int \frac{-9}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx = \int \frac{-1}{x}\,dx + \int \frac{x}{x^2+9}\,dx = -\ln|x| + C + \int \frac{x}{x^2+9}\,dx.\end{align*}

We evaluated the last integral earlier in this problem and found
$\int \frac{x}{x^2+9}\,dx = \frac12 \ln(x^2+9).$ So

\begin{align*}\int \frac{-9}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx = \frac12Â \ln(x^2+9) - \ln|x| + C,\end{align*}

and therefore the final answer is

\begin{align*}\int \frac{x^2-9}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx = \ln(x^2+9) - \ln|x| + C.\end{align*}

We want to evaluate the integral

\begin{align*}\int \frac{x^2-9}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx.\end{align*}

This can be rewritten as

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{2x^2-(x^2+9)}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx &= \int \frac{2x^2}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx - \int \frac{x^2+9}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx \\
&= \int \frac{2x}{x^2+9}\,dx - \int \frac{1}{x}\,dx.\end{align*}

We evaluate the first integral using the substitution \emph{u =
x\^{}2+9}, \emph{du = 2xdx}, the second integral is just
\emph{ln\textbar{}x\textbar{} + C}. Hence

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{2x^2-(x^2+9)}{x(x^2+9)}\,dx &= \int \frac1{u}\,du - \ln|x| - C \\
&= \ln|u| - \ln|x| - C \\
&= \ln|x^2+9| - \ln|x| - C\end{align*}

\emph{Note: Since C is a constant, we can write -C or +D, for D=-C.
Either solution is fine.}
